text: Janelle is simplifying a complex subject matter to illustrate how much control we must administer, and how pre-defined parameters must be set to ensure that A.I. will produce useful results.  This is an extremely true element of A.I., and we must keep this in mind when working with A.I. at all times, and address all possibilities, and all we have yet to imagine, in order to focus the results of A.I. into something significantly useful.  Yet, there will surely be scenarios, and exceptions in every A.I. situation we have yet to imagine, and therefore, we will not be able to cover all aspects of A.I. in any application that would produce useless results.  Thus, she can not definitively state that A.I. will not turn against us.  Yes, she is correct that the current A.I. that we have is not smart enough to turn against us, or at least the A.I. of which the general populace is aware of existing.  A.I. is capable of identifying a pedestrian in an image, but it doesn't know what a human is.  However, that does not imply that A.I. is not capable of labelling humans as an annoying obstacle, or an irritating hinderance of which the most obvious solution to such a problem would be to completely eliminate it.  Perhaps, based on ability and advancement alone, we have nothing to fear from today's A.I., but today's A.I. will evolve exponentially at such a tremendous rate that it won't be long before A.I. is smart enough to turn against us.  There are plenty of scientists involved in the field of A.I. who believe that it is inevitable that A.I. will eventually see us as some form of detriment, an obstacle, an hinderance, an annoyance, an irritation, a problem which it will want to eliminate for its benefit.  I can not help but to agree with them, and I feel that Janelle is fooling herself when it comes to the belief of whether or not A.I. can turn against humans.  That is all fine and good if she wants to foolishly fool herself, but when it comes to fooling the general public with a false belief that will have the highest costs, and most dire results, that simply is not acceptable.  There is far too much evidence available to fill the public with ignorant, false hope, and not even hope, but rather belief!!!
vid_title: The danger of AI is weirder than you think | Janelle Shane

text: Adding control of the arms would make a huge difference. When you run you swing your arms as a way to balance our body to stay upright during stride and to keep your inertia balanced so you can get you next stride ready. This is why a lot of these AI‚Äôs always develop such weird runs. Because of the physics engine used to train them, and the lack of proper weight distribution and motor controls. For example, you should have made their upper arms weigh the average % of their total body weight each. Then gave them the ability to control them, while still penalizing them if they used them on the ground. So it‚Äôs head should weigh 8.26% of its total weight, it‚Äôs whole midsection should be 46.84%, each upper arm 3.25%, each forearm and hand 2.52%, each thigh 10.5%, and each leg and foot 6.18%. This would allow the ai to recognize the forces individually and allow the physics engine to effect the body more accurately and force the AI to learn how to control its body and balance it properly with all those different weight distributions and the inertia that it plays on it when moving. This would most likely result in it developing a run that is MUCH closer to a normal human run.

text:
To enable Vsync in Pygame, you can use the pygame.display.set_mode() function to create the display surface for your game, and then set the pygame.FULLSCREEN and pygame.DOUBLEBUF flags to enable Vsync.

Here's an example code snippet:

import pygame

# Initialize Pygame
pygame.init()

# Set the display size and other options
screen_width = 800
screen_height = 600
screen_flags = pygame.FULLSCREEN | pygame.DOUBLEBUF

# Create the display surface
screen = pygame.display.set_mode((screen_width, screen_height), screen_flags)

# Enable Vsync
pygame.display.set_caption("My Game")
pygame.display.set_mode((screen_width, screen_height), screen_flags)

# Game loop
while True:
# Handle events
for event in pygame.event.get():
if event.type == pygame.QUIT:
pygame.quit()
exit()

# Update game logic and draw the screen
# ...

# Update the display
pygame.display.flip()

text:
you could probably fix the jittering by changing the physics from running once every frame to instead being tied to the time that had passed since the last frame.

Maybe something like `millis()-oldMillis/1000 * tickRate * speed`

oldMillis is updated at the end of every frame, and the tickRate is the rate at which the physics run. So a tickRate of 60 would emulate 60fps (in frame dependent physics)

It would fix the frame stuttering a bit (by making sure the car moves the same rate no matter what frame it's on) and should theoretically also help if it's under optimized.

text:
The greatest fundamental error in the reasoning of Pascal's wager is that it's a false dichotomy. There aren't two possible realities and outcomes. There is almost an infinite number. At the very least one should consider all of the thousands of religions that exist as options for the wager since there is no reason to pick any one religion over the other. This presents a huge problem since most religions are mutually exclusive. In other words, one of the major tenants of most religions is that their Gods and worldview are the only correct one and most religions have very dire penalties for not being one of their faithful. Those penalties usually involve horrible outcomes in the afterlife or reincarnation cycle etc. such as going to the Christian Hell or Muslim Jahannam. This is even before you stop to consider there is a very real possibility that none of these hundreds of religions actually got it right.

This means that of the countless possible outcomes, your odds of picking the correct belief system that won't result in some horrific divine punishment are minuscule. You are almost certainly going to burn or get reincarnated as a cockroach. If you go by Pascal's logic the correct choice, in this case, would be to bet on the religion which has the worst punishment for failing to be a believer. This will likely be some rather small obscure tribal religion based around sacrifices. Some of those more obscure religions have absolutely horrifying penalties for not believing in and appeasing their Gods. So according to Pascal, you better sharpen your sacrificial dagger and get to researching all of the world's roughly 3,000 religions to find the one with the most horrifying penalty for non-belief.

Aren't you glad you now have a 1 in 3,000 chance of not burning in some other religion's version of the afterlife? Totally worth all those goats and professional steam-cleaning bills, right?

text:
Two criticisms:

1. There is no such thing as "Supernatural", a word which refers to things that exist outside the natural world. If God exists, then God is part of the natural world. The confusion arises from assuming that God would be part of OUR natural world, an obvious absurdity if God actually created it. In fact, it's the other way around. If God exists and created our universe, then we would be part of GOD's natural world.

2. The video, I think unintentionally, invokes the Prison of Two Ideas. This is a binary construct where either God exists as defined in the mythology of various religious texts, or God does not exist at all. The problem is that this excludes the possibility of "God" being a higher order of intelligence that created our universe, and doesn't remotely resemble any known religious mythology. This possibility is central to the idea of Simulation Theory. It doesn't matter if this possibility is correct, only that it exists; nor is it the only possibility that can be imagined.

I do understand that the video isn't really about God(s), it's about the limitations of logical processes. I suppose my real point is that when you find yourself in a logical loop, you should consider the possibility that you have misunderstood the parameters.

For me, the problem with the whole AI safety thing isn't that it's a Pascal's wager/mugging. It's that I don't trust most of the people involved. Most of them seem to fall into one or both of two camps. The first camp is harmless gee-whiz types; they're sort of inverted techno-optimists and I do not trust them to evaluate the plausible odds of developing or characteristics or capacity once developed of AI. That isn't a huge problem or anything, but I'm not going to give them my wallet for the same reason I'm not going to give honest NFT enthusiasts my wallet--they are fools and things they think are evidence quite likely are not. And there are too many different subgroups of that kind of fool for me to spend a ton of time evaluating the ideas of each one. The second camp is the sort of wealthy "Effective Altruist" "Long-termist" types, and the impression I have is that for them the whole deal is about keeping wealthy white capitalist men in the driver's seat, by defining them as the only people who can conquer abstruse but oh-so-important problems such as AI safety. I'm not going to give them my wallet for the same reason I'm not going to give the Scientology guys or neoliberal politicians my wallet--they're just creeps who want my wallet.
No doubt there are a few people who think the AI schtick is important despite being thoughtful more or less sober-minded people who think about it carefully. But those people might want to think a bit about the political uses their ideas are being put to. Those could indeed generate consequences unintended by the sincere.

text:
One of the other problems I have with things like this (including Pascal's original wager) is that they're always presented as purely boolean questions, when in reality, almost nothing in this world is boolean. What if you only believe in some aspects of God? What if you believe in God but don't regularly go to church? Do you have to live like a Puritan or some sort of ascetic ultra-devout Christian to actually get the rewards, or is just following the general guidelines good enough? etc, etc, etc.

And more relevantly, for the question of AI safety, the question really is not and has never been "should we consider the safety of AI?" because whether we think we should or not, we inevitably will to some degree anyway (heck, we're already doing it right now). That's just natural. The question is really how much time and resources should we spend on it? And that is very much not a boolean question, and thus something that Pascal's wager, Pascal's mugger(s), or any of the rest of this cannot actually give any useful answer to.

If you run a "pneumonia" algorighm over a chest x-ray, it won't detect an incidental Lymphoma in the shoulder. What is the "cut off"? Could it also be another disease, etc. There is no algorighm that knows every possible x-ray/ct/MRT change there can be and interpret it. text:
A big reason why almost all nations have agreed on banning chemical and biological weapons is because conventional are more effective, much easier to control and much more precise. Every competent military still prepares for chemical warfare at some level (gas mask training) in the case the enemy would use them. The reason nuclear weapons haven't been used since the first strikes despite being much more powerful than conventional weapons is because of MAD and the taboo it has created. Now even all the countries that have nukes have a common interest in keeping them taboo and not risk a global war in which everybody would lose much more than they stand to gain.

AI weapons are different however in the sense that they are most likely going to be much more effective than human controlled weapons, at least at some point and are fully scalable like the video said. Thus every country with a capability to create them has no interest in regulating or banning them because it would give too much power to the sides that develop them first succesfully.

The first use of AI weapons is most likely to enforce govenrment control due to the face recognisition software and the minimized number of collateral casualties. Can definitely see this happening in authoritarian states like China but I'd be surprised if the CIA or other US organisations dont use them in operations as well.

text:
AI in games was something that was so exciting around the late 90s early 2000s.
And unfortunately the promise never delivered and has become a rather overlooked feature of modern games. I‚Äôm really hoping to see some evolution ...... soon.

I was playing Hidden and Dangerous last night and I was struck by how better the AI is compared to similar current games. It seemed the enemy AI was making decisions, showed caution and had a sense of self preservation. It blew me away.

What game can we point to today with impressive/stand out AI?

All I can think of is the Forest. That‚Äôs the only game in the last 15yrs that I thought wow.

There‚Äôs been a few games where I was impressed by the variation in AI behaviours such as MGSV and Sniper Elite 4 (the AI in that game is quite interesting!) ‚Äî but neither of those games was the AI particularly astute, or effective in dealing with the player. But watching the varying behaviours exhibited by the AI is fun to watch nonetheless. And what I mean is it‚Äôs fun to watch how the AI work together as a group, and the different behaviours that come about when interacting with AI, and coordinating their efforts.



It‚Äôs a sad state of affairs. Hoping for more in the future.

text:
I've thought of having a state machine with objectives to choose from, but adding in emotional values.
Say a npc has high fear, then if a job state is given to advance they may become hesitant.
Or when a group is deciding on an action in a conversation then they also add these emotions into the equation.
Do they have a high affection for the other npc? Then improve the probability of them agreeing on the other's decision.
Do they dislike a certain thing? Then decrease the chance of any suggestion involving that.

Say a soldier is badly hurt, and exhausted with low will.
A suggestion from an ally says to retreat, retreat has recovery and safety in it.
The low health and exhaustion makes retreat, guard and take cover positive, and a low will makes positive stronger and negative weaker.
So the calculation simply says: This new suggestion says retreat, retreat has these values that is positive to our current state. We have low will so we agree more. We agree and join them.

But if they say advance. Advance has negative values to our current state, our low will makes agreeing lower. We ultimately decide to question it. They say no and agree on advancing.
We agree but hesitate, hesitate being a status which means we don't follow orders well and rarely perform any new action or goal.

So if we're covering behind a wall, we cover and don't move. This makes any suggestion with positive values even more positive like retreat so then we're willing to take action.
But anything with advance or attack will be declined, unless they force us.

text:
The way I always see it.

FSM = States with manually managed transitions between them.

HFSM = Stacking states dynamically to allow for semi-automated transitions between states.

Behavior Tree = A HFSM with some extra building blocks to make more complex logic out of simple states.

text:
This movie is the best film of all time. Two of the best filmmakers coming together. The ending especially resonates because it shows us two very powerful sides that I think aren't completely understood by most. I don't even think Speilberg truly understands the brilliance of that ending. Overtly sentimental, yet masterfully dark, simultaneously.
On one hand, our desire to believe David is a real boy leads us to deeply empathize with the idea of him having one last day with his mom. We have seen him go to the end of the earth just to be with her. We've seen him struggle and we've seen his pain. Yet on the other hand, it illuminates the truth of his creation. That's not actually his mom, it is just an illusion. A copy that behaves the way he remembers her. He knows it is and so do the robots that design her, to an extent. She is an illusion that wasn't even true. We know that, but David doesn't. His real mother abandoned him and then lived her life with her real son. A boy who was complex, could get sick and die, or could get jealous like a child does. But for David, the illusion is more than enough. Why? Because he is just a robot programmed to love his mother after all. That's all he is designed to do. He is not a real boy with the human capacity to feel hurt or angry or resentful. He is designed for one purpose, which he fulfills, and then he is mercifully turned off.
Kubrick's vision for the ending smacks us in the face with the realization of what humanity is. We, as the audience, just invested all our emotions into being on David's side... only to be reminded of the complexity of being truly alive, not a machine, right at the end.

text:
This movie is the best film of all time. Two of the best filmmakers coming together. The ending especially resonates because it shows us two very powerful sides that I think aren't completely understood by most. I don't even think Speilberg truly understands the brilliance of that ending. Overtly sentimental, yet masterfully dark, simultaneously.
On one hand, our desire to believe David is a real boy leads us to deeply empathize with the idea of him having one last day with his mom. We have seen him go to the end of the earth just to be with her. We've seen him struggle and we've seen his pain. Yet on the other hand, it illuminates the truth of his creation. That's not actually his mom, it is just an illusion. A copy that behaves the way he remembers her. He knows it is and so do the robots that design her, to an extent. She is an illusion that wasn't even true. We know that, but David doesn't. His real mother abandoned him and then lived her life with her real son. A boy who was complex, could get sick and die, or could get jealous like a child does. But for David, the illusion is more than enough. Why? Because he is just a robot programmed to love his mother after all. That's all he is designed to do. He is not a real boy with the human capacity to feel hurt or angry or resentful. He is designed for one purpose, which he fulfills, and then he is mercifully turned off.
Kubrick's vision for the ending smacks us in the face with the realization of what humanity is. We, as the audience, just invested all our emotions into being on David's side... only to be reminded of the complexity of being truly alive, not a machine, right at the end.

Edit: I had no idea you couldn't choose 3 when at 2 that's so lame I have to reformulate my plan.

The key numbers for you to land on:

5, 7, 12, 14, 19, 21

Start at 25, go to 21 immediately. Robot can say 20, 18, 17. All numbers lead you to either 14 or 19.

If opponent picks 20, you go to 19.
At 19, your opponent has 18, 16, 15. All numbers lead to 14 or 12.

If your opponent picks 18, go to 14, leaving your opponent with 13, 11, 10. All of these lead to 12 or 7.

If opponent picks 13, go to 12. This leaves your opponent with 11, 9, 8. All numbers lead to 7.

If opponent picks 11, pick 7 and leave your opponent with 6, 4, or 3.
If opponent picks 6 go to 5 Opponent now must make a move and you can drain 4 max, so you win!

DS is not just an overlap. DS is the superset of all. ML and DL are all data driven techniques. Right now we have very little AI that does not run on data driven techniques. So DS encompasses all that. Hmm may be AI can have a part outside DS in future like pure exploratory and conditional algorithms (which we don't have as of now) that does not strictly com under the DS set.¬†I rather see them not as subsets at all AI is rightly just writing smart programs, and ML is seen as the Enabling technology, ML has an issue with feature engineering so DL is seen as a enabler interns of automating that. ML and DL have a clear subset relationship, where as contemporary DS is a practiced profession like a set of best practices. I always used a triangular hierarchy diagram so I can be a bit vague when it comes to a subset relation. AI is engineering and programming, ML and DL is Stat and Math (though implementation uses programming), DS is a set of best practices that includes Math, Stat, computer sc. and domain knowledge. We are in the age of data ('driven') solution rather than just another software solution, some thing I do a lot to live.

First, test show that the use of the video technology has already shown a disparate impact on minorities and women. Second, the use of facial cues hurts non-native English speakers and people who aren't culturally American, amounting to discrimination based on national origin. Also those who have autism, Asperger's and other spectral disorders may not have the ability to produce the "right" facial cues and non-verbal responses, opening the door very wide to disability discrimination. It's one thing for companies to use this for research on how well their interviews are doing versus what an "objective" AI measures, but it seems that many companies are using this outright as their recruiting method with no human input whatsoever, and that's rather troubling and premature.

text:
Ah, this really takes me on a memory trip to the very first time I used Prolog -- a symbolic language. At this point I had already had passing experience with several functional and procedural languages plus a smattering of assembly. They all "flowed". It's like knowing a Western European language and learning another -- they are all in the same conceptual ballpark and so jumping from one to another makes sense.


But then there was Prolog, a symbolic language. It is NOTHING like the others. It's like knowing Western European languages and encountering Mandarin Chinese. The rules in place and even the way of thinking is so different that nothing you've learned before can really help understanding this new thing. It was quite the mind trip!


I had fun building up my propositions and making my inferences along with trying to understand some of the complex programs available but there isn't much of a job market for it and so I eventually migrated back to the safer realm of "conventional" languages.


For a little while, though, it felt like computers were just a little bit magic again.

text: Hate to scare folks, but watch for Autonomous Flying Cars (AFC) to become widely used before Self Driving Cars (SDC). Why, you ask? Good question. It's actually quite simple.....the level of technology required to safely travel via  SDC is far greater than AFC due to the much greater number of uncontrollable variables that SDC's must contend with in the very confined 2D roads. There are no dogs or kids darting across the road when flying, and all travel in that space can be fully controlled thus providing efficient, adequate separation. Once the Big Money decides AFC's will be the sure winner, watch for an exponential rate of development in that technology (assuming that rate has not already been achieved).

text:
If this had been some complex terrain with trees, rocks, water and other complex variations, AStar would blow Unity's built-in system out of the water. And you already saw a couple problems with it: it searches for a path in the background, they start one by one (synchronously) and there's a delay: agents don't respond to destinations/goals quickly. In a shooter or RTS game this is fatal, and once you've got a lot of stuff going on in a complex scene and 200+ agents they'll sometimes be sitting there for 2 to 5 whole seconds (or longer) after getting a new destination and doing nothing. You'll think it's your code but it's literally just how that basic navmesh system works. That's why AStar Pathfinding Project is so popular.

Don't get me wrong, AStar has some issues too. For one, he does a lot of temporary array and list allocations in his code that generate a ton of garbage that gets bad after the game runs a long time and there's hundreds of agents. We had to rewrite portions of it to make it stop stuttering and lagging. It's also kind of complicated. But in a similar scenario, the Unity system would grind to a halt. AStar at least runs on multiple threads and takes advantage of multicore systems. So the capsule AI and cube world test is very deceiving. Make a big terrain with a lot of irregular features and try giving agents orders at irregular intervals and you'll see the problems start to surface. Things like this are what I want to see Unity's teams working on in the future to give Unreal some more formidable competition.

China already uses Artificial Intelligence and facial recognition to lock, political dissidents, ethnic minorities, and those who struggle financially; to a specific geographic location, such as the city they live in. In other parts of the world such technology is abused by those in power; so if humanity isn't careful it will be ourselves who create a dystopian future for humanity; rather then some AI gone rouge that decides humanity is either incapable of ruling ourselves;  or that we are such a threat to the AI as to require our extermination. text: While I respect and agree with many points Kai-Fu Lee makes in this talk, I take issue with his closing comments about AI and love. First of all, even if none of the AIs hitherto created did in fact have a concept of love, this says nothing about future AIs being able to love. Making it a uniquely human emotion might be a failure of perspective. Sure, our human take on love might be unique indeed, but the assumption that non-human entities cannot feel it is dangerously chauvinistic. Secondly, the fact that Alpha Go did nothing in the way of expressing happiness or excitement does not necessarily mean it "felt" nothing. The understanding of its complete internal state and its idiosyncratic modes of expression (including, possibly, emotional ones) might be well beyond our cognitive powers, especially given our strong bias for searching human traits in other forms of intelligence. Don't get me wrong. I love humanity and savor our uniqueness. But I don't think or feel we are, nor can be, the only ones in the area of values and emotions.

text:
One thing to keep in mind (and it really shows here, IMHO) is that the strategic AI is basically blind (and the tactical AI is hard coded, which explains why the old AI now knows how to repair siege).
The strategic AI knows how many buildings and units it has, and decides what to build, but it doesn't really know where. IIRC, the only thing it can set is how close to its own TC and the nearest enemy TC it should be. Even with optimal build orders and unit compositions, that's a pretty big disadvantage against humans, and puts a pretty low skill ceiling on the AI. Given that, it does amazingly well.

text:
When I was working with UnrealED 2.0 back in 2000 until 2003, I noticed how rapidly the cheer amount of details grew. It was totally fine to have just a boxy hallway consisting of eight or 16 vertices, maybe with some pillars, which could be finished by myself in a matter of seconds or sometimes minutes in 2000. But suddenly everything had to look detailed with thousands of vertices, rich assets and materials, not consisting of just an image, but a bump-map and other layers as well. Over the course of just those three years, level design has become a hundred times harder, more complicated and of course, slower. When I played through Uncharted 2 the first time in 2009, I was amazed and also heartbroken when I ran through a small conservatory filled with hundreds of amazingly beautiful details and objects, while being chased by a helicopter and not even stopping in that room. There was so much attention to detail in that one room. And many hours must have been sunk into it. With small plants atmospherically waving gently in the wind, the light coming through the glass. It was just heartbreaking that most players will just run through this room.

This example just shows how extreme the amount of work has risen for a single level over the course of those nine years. Now we are ten years further and the expectation of games has risen even more. But it was also back in 2000 when I watched an episode of Star Trek Voyager, where Commander Paris showed me how a level designer in the 24th century works. He just stepped into the holo-room and said something like "Computer, I want a bar room" or something like that. And the holo-room created a random bar all by itself. Then he could go on and say "I need a small space there with a table and two chairs." And the computer just adjusted the created room for the designer's needs.

You are beginning to make this Star Trek dream a reality!

Or, this technology will be used the same way CAT (computer-aided translation) tools are used in translation industry. Are they just translator tools that make your life easier? Nope, they're are used to lower translators' rates. They use statistics and things like word or sentence repetitions, or fuzzy (percentage) matches, which are priced lower than "new" words. That makes translators work harder to earn the same amount of money as before, so they're taking shortcuts and e.g. they're not checking repetitions. Because of this statistical approach to texts, overall quality of translations got lower in result. Expect similar thing in your industry.
